{
  "texts": [
    "Diseases can cause or be associated with other diseases as a symptom or sign.",
    "The distinction between symptoms and signs is very subtle; while both are abnormalities that may indicate a disease, the former are subjective to the patient and cannot be measured by tests or observed by physicians (e.g., pain or loss of appetite).",
    "On the other hand, a sign can be measured or observed (e.g., high blood pressure, poor lung function).",
    "Across n = 832 texts, there were a total 4,065 rare diseases, 1,814 diseases, 316 symptoms, and 3,317 signs.",
    "Rare diseases and signs were more common than diseases and symptoms, accounting for 77% of all entities in the corpus (Table 1)."
  ]
}